{
  "doc_id": "28931",
  "text": "In 2 nd -tier CAP inpatients, Gram-negative bacteria were also commonly isolated. K. pneumoniae was found among the five most frequent bacteria in all three articles describing etiologies of radiologically-confirmed CAP, using cultures as diagnostic tools. Its prevalence reached 35.5% in positive sputum cultures in one setting in Thailand [CITATION_1] . B. pseudomallei was also among the most frequent pathogens, found in up to 24.0% of blood cultures of bacteremic patients in one setting [CITATION_2] and in 7.7% of positive sputum cultures in another setting [CITATION_3] . S. pneumoniae was identified in 22.4% of admitted patients with CAP in one setting [CITATION_4] and 17% of bacteremic patients in another [CITATION_5] . Other causes included H. influenzae, Staphylococcus aureus, Escherichia coli, Acinetobacter spp. and Pseudomonas aeruginosa [CITATION_6] . Studies looking for atypical pneumonia pathogens at the 2 nd -tier level identified Legionella longbeachae, M. pneumoniae, C. pneumoniae, Coxiella burnetti and Legionella pneumophilla [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] .",
